&lt;h2&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Band 8a Specialist Clinical Pharmacist - Diabetes &lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;We have the exciting opportunity to join us as Specialist Clinical Pharmacist  for Diabetes at University Hospitals Birmingham. This is an important leadership role within the pharmacy service recognising that the diabetes department at University Hospitals Birmingham has 10,000 patients registered with the diabetes clinics, accounting for nearly 26,000 visits annually. You will be involved in quality improvement and clinical research projects allied to the diabetes speciality and support medicines optimisation with the clinics and ward based services. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;There will be a strong emphasis on supporting you in developing clinical leadership and mentoring skills to the next level. With the support of the Principal Pharmacist, you will complete core directorate activities such as reporting and analysis of medicines expenditure in order to optimise cost-effective prescribing, clinical governance and risk management activities. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;You will be taking on enhanced roles relating to education and training such as developing training programmes and supervising/tutoring less experienced members of the team including pre-registration pharmacists.  The Trust has close links with Aston University and you will be involved with supporting undergraduate pharmacy teaching. You will contribute to the delivery of formal and informal education and development programmes, including the Diploma in Clinical Pharmacy, and our rotational programme for band 6 and 7 clinical pharmacists. Teaching of medical and non-medical support staff within the diabetes specialty will also be a key part of the role. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;You will form part of an on-site Pharmacy team at your base hospital which is integrated with other Pharmacy services around the Trust, and will also work as part of our broader clinical pharmacy team, contributing to local and national initiatives to develop and enhance services. A feature of this role is the close working with the wider multi-disciplinary team which includes diabetes specialist nurses, podiatry teams, dieticians, psychologists as well as the team of specialist diabetes and endocrinology doctors. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;As part of the leadership team for Pharmacy Medicine services, you will work alongside and be supported by other lead pharmacists in the team, which may include spending time on sites other than your base site.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Ideally, you will hold or be willing to work towards a NMP qualification. Significant experience of working in a hospital pharmacy is essential.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;For an informal discussion please contact Shahzad Razaq, Principal Pharmacist Medicine and Anti-Infectives (&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;shahzad.razaq@heartofengland.nhs.uk&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;) or Dr Ateeq Syed, Consultant Diabetes &amp; Endocrinology (&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;ateeq.syed@heartofengland.nhs.uk&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;) via switchboard 0121 424 2000.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span&gt;Interview date: 25&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;th&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt; November 2020&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
